account status: @muji_net A major challenge for autonomous vehicles ‚Äì which we faced during the pilot program ‚Äì was unexpected roadwork that had appeared on the route. We are proud that GACHA handled this situation well.

@muji_net The program lasted for 5 weeks (14 days of operations) and in total, the autonomous shuttle bus drove 330km. A majority of the passengers reported that they felt very safe during their rides. All in all, we had 278 passengers, an average of 20 passengers/day.

Last week we wrapped up GACHA‚Äôs first #selfdriving pilot program in #Espoo #Finland. 

Sensible 4 and MUJI @muji_net would like to thank everyone who participated and gave us valuable feedback.

#UAS2020 Episode I's Closing Keynote was delivered by Kirk Shaffer, the FAA's Associate Administrator for Airports. Shaffer opened by highlighting the dramatic progress aviation has made in only a little over a century - from a manned glider to #unmanned technology.

Reynolds also spoke about the path forward for funding and building infrastructure including vertiports. Public and private funding sources sharing the cost is likely the most efficient way forward, she said, as both provide benefits for such major projects.

The conversation also turned towards the importance of social consciousness when attempting to integrate new technologies and add urban infrastructure: ‚ÄúWhat are the costs we‚Äôre paying for this integration as a society?‚Äù Dietrich asked, highlighting this issue.

Anna Dietrich, Co-Executive Director of the Community Air Mobility Initiative, said that a major goal of UAM integration is to ‚Äú...integrate it in a way that benefits the maximum number of people.‚Äù

‚ÄúThis city is built upon decades of decision making about the way people move around," Reynolds said, clarifying one of the most difficult aspects of integrating UAM: that existing infrastructure must be either built upon or built around.

Seleta Reynolds, General Manager of the Los Angeles Department of Transportation, opened by focusing on the importance of making sure the city always remains a healthy place where its residents can thrive, especially where building UAM infrastructure is concerned.

#UAS2020 Day 2's final Keynote (but not last session!) addressed Urban Air Mobility and the steps to integrate it into large cities. Anna Dietrich and Seleta Reynolds provided their expert insight and discussed the next steps and safe paths forward on UAM.

retweet status: The code did indeed work, but it's been a while since I've had to tune it. I started with parameters from @diyrobocars, where a 2-meter error means you're way off the track. Here, the track is ~8m wide, so the first attempt resulted in it driving straight into the weeds.
after much debugging, @a1k0n managed a full lap of @ThunderhillPark West yesterday with a 1/5 scale car. https://t.co/Ss6Lz435Ti

The points where the green dots are right on the edges of the track are where it's sorta iffy where the car will actually go offroading. Gonna try computing a narrower racing line and it should be fine. I'm getting 21-22 satellites in view on the GPS, precision is about 0.5m https://t.co/Xp9rYedGVe
Watching this from a chase car was an extremely surreal experience, I have to say. It worked, but I think the data I was using was slightly off. https://t.co/03lw06sUnS

@EllerbachMaxime @SmallpixelCar @circuitlaunch @diyrobocars @NVIDIAEmbedded There's a separate tool to generate a policy from every point on the track at every heading angle using CUDA, yes, but @SmallpixelCar is using this scipy.optimize-based tool which generates a minimum curvature line within the boundaries of the track: https://t.co/UfdaCYldPC

@EllerbachMaxime @SmallpixelCar @circuitlaunch @diyrobocars @NVIDIAEmbedded He's talking about this tool:
https://t.co/DIXbeMfCSe - you define a track by a series of circular arcs connected by straight lines, and then it can solve for a minimum-curvature loop within the track boundary constraints.

@a1k0n @circuitlaunch @diyrobocars @NVIDIAEmbedded Yes, I was able to run. After tied different tracks, I could generate a track in one hour. I also found you could not use more than 180 degree of a circle. Otherwise the program will not work...if you know what I am talking about.

I modified one of my Cycloid PCBs for GPS, RC input, and brushless RPM sensor input. It's a bit hacked up but it works and I had it on hand. Spent the morning making wire harnesses and reflashing the firmware so that if it runs away or goes out of RC range it stops. https://t.co/z7HTd1x2Zb

7/7 Later this year, we‚Äôll share more on the safety framework we‚Äôve developed to ensure the safe performance of our self-driving technology as we continue to scale our fully driverless operations.
6/7 We also expect our values to fluctuate depending on release timing, geography and other non-engineering reasons, which invalidates time-series comparisons.

5/7 This is even more the case in 2019 and 2020, as we are now developing our 5th-generation Waymo Driver in Silicon Valley, SF and LA. We don't think CA disengagement data should be used to compare performance, or judge readiness or competency.

4/7 This real-world production performance is largely unrelated to our California testing outputs. At this stage our real-world driving in California is predominately engineering development, and not production releases.

3/7 Most of our large-scale real-world driving, which is critical for full-system validation (including validating the realism of our simulator) comes from Phoenix. Indeed, our production releases are already serving thousands of Waymo riders in Phoenix.

2/7 While much of the development, learning, and validation of the Waymo Driver comes through billions of miles driven within our simulation environments, our real-world driving experience is primarily outside of California, in markets like Detroit and Phoenix.

1/7 We appreciate what the California DMV was trying to do when creating this requirement, but the disengagement metric does not provide relevant insights into the capabilities of the Waymo Driver or distinguish its performance from others in the self-driving space.
